In order to show this relationship, we must first recall what an annuity is. Basically, an annuity is a fixed amount that is paid each period. Since in this problem, the timeframe is not given, we will assume perpetuity which means that the fixed amount is paid for an infinite/indefinite number of years. This means that the formula for this perpetuity is given as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Present value (PV) of perpetuity}&=\dfrac{\text{Cashflow}}{\text{Rate}}
\end{aligned}$$

Using the formula above, we can then solve for the present value annuity based on the perpetuity given. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{PV annuity}&=\dfrac{\text{Cashflow}}{(1+\text{Rate})^\text{Time}}
\end{aligned}$$

However, since we are using perpetuity, then the present annuity value will become:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{PV annuity}&=\dfrac{\text{Cashflow}}{(1+\text{Rate})^1}+\dfrac{\text{Cashflow}}{(1+\text{Rate})^2} +\ldots+ \dfrac{\text{Cashflow}}{(1+\text{Rate})^\text{Time}}
\end{aligned}$$

Using the formula above, we can then solve for the future value annuity based on the perpetuity given. This can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Future value annuity}&=\text{Cashflow} \times(1+\text{Rate})^\text{Time}
\end{aligned}$$

However, since we are using perpetuity, then the future value annuity will become:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{FV annuity}&=\text{Cashflow} \times(1+\text{Rate})^1 +\text{Cashflow} \times(1+\text{Rate})^2+ \ldots + \text{Cashflow} \times(1+\text{Rate})^\text{Time}
\end{aligned}$$
